DOMAIN_OVERVIEW:
This domain examines wage determination, income trends, public sector wages, wage repression,
and labor market dualization in Germany and Europe. Focus on real wage stagnation post-2000,
Hartz reforms (2003-2005), collective bargaining coverage decline, public vs. private sector
wage differentials, and wage-housing burden connections. Key findings: Real wages stagnated/
declined 2000-2015, with particularly sharp impacts on low-wage sector. Public sector wages
showed varied trends with recent catching up. Collective bargaining coverage declined in
private sector but remained strong in public sector. These wage dynamics are critical for
explaining housing burden changes.

RELEVANCE_TO_PROJECT:
Essential for testing Hypothesis 3 (public sector wage repression affects housing burden)
and Hypothesis 4 (80%+ of housing burden change explained by wage income changes). Provides
evidence on income-side determinants of housing cost burden.

KEY_DEBATES:
- Hartz reforms' impact on wage levels and distribution
- Public-private sector wage gaps and trends
- Role of unions and collective bargaining in wage determination
- Wage stagnation vs. productivity growth disconnect
====================================================================
